descript.abstract: U.S. MapData Landmark Points represents locations and proper names for airports, amusement centers, apartment buildings, bus terminals, campgrounds, cemeteries, city halls, convents, monasteries, custodial facilities, educational institutions, religious institutions, employment centers, penitentiaries, fire stations, golf courses, government centers, halfway houses, hospitals, hotels, resorts, spas, housing facilities, industrial buildings, islands, jails, landmarks, lookout towers, marinas, military installations, mountain peaks, national parks, national forests, nursing homes, office buildings, open spaces, orphanages, police stations, post offices, public libraries, shopping centers, state parks, local parks, towers, trailer courts, train stations, and other landmark type features within United States. Data extracted from the USGS Geographic Names Information System (GNIS).
descript.purpose: U.S. MapData Landmark Points provides point locations, proper names and attributes for landmark features.
descript.supplinf: Largest scale when displaying the data: 1:100,000.

citeinfo.title: ESRI® MapData™
citeinfo.othercit: The data is derived from a variety of sources, including the United States Census Bureau, the United States Geological Survey (USGS), the United States Department of Transportation (USDOT), and the United States Postal Service® (USPS®).

procstep.procsv: ESRI® MapLoader, ArcView® GIS 3, ArcGIS® 9, ArcSDE®
procstep.procdesc: The following steps were performed by ESRI: Selected all counties in the ESRI MapLoader, extracted and then appended the landmarks into one data set. Converted Hawaii and Pacific Island areas to North American Datum of 1983 (NAD83) by splitting it from the rest of the United States; converting it to NAD83; then merging them together. Changed DUPFLAG attribute to LABEL_FLAG attribute. Converted the data set to SDC. Created the projection file (.prj) and spatial indices.
The following steps were performed by ESRI: Reduced the attribute widths for CLASS and STATE.

dataqual.logic: The shapefile is converted to SDC (Smart Data Compression) format using either ESRI SDC Data Development Kit Professional 2 (DDKP2) or tools in ArcGIS. The SDC data set is then loaded into ArcSDE® to verify and validate the geometry.
dataqual.complete: After processing, the data set is checked for drawing display and number of records and file sizes compared with source materials.
